 in contemporary South Africa. She also analyses current renegotiations of popular repertoires, particularly songs and dances related to the Struggle, revivals of classic European and South African protest plays, new history plays and specific racial and ethnic histories and identities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollective memoryzSouth Africa. 0aSouth African dramaxHistory and criticism. 0aTheaterxPolitical aspectszSouth Africa. 0aTheater--Political aspects--South Africa. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / General.2bisacsh  aMbeki.  aSouth Africa-Mali project.  aSouth African performance.  aTruth and Reconciliation Commission archive.  acultural identities.  acultural practitioners.  amemory.  anational identities.  apolitical crisis.  apost-apartheid South Africa.  asocial structure.  astate sanctioned-performances.  atheatrical engagements.  averbatim narratives.1 aHutchison, Yvette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610323940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526103239423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526103239/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles